{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487003"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:53:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:53:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"229"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/229"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.58,0.08,0.15,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"229"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90834"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/229"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"229"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74897"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3810"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"238"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31133"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90834"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a five-month history of vague upper abdominal discomfort and fatigue. Her appetite has diminished recently and she has lost some weight. She denies a fever. She has a medical history of hypertension and she had a total thyroidectomy for hyperthyroidism 15 years ago. Her medications include perindopril and levothyroxine. She is a reformed smoker with a 15 pack-year history. She drinks about two glasses of wine at weekends. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she appears well. Her pulse rate is 76/min, blood pressure 132/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 17/min and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The rest of the physical examination is normal. \u00a0An abdominal CT scan is performed and a representative arterial phase image is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most likely cause of the lesion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hepatic cysts","Metastatic liver disease","Hepatic abscess","Hepatic haemangioma","Hydatid disease"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an abdominal contrast enhanced CT scan in the arterial phase, showing\u00a0several hypodense lesions with ring enhancement within the liver (Image).\u00a0Taken together with the history, the CT findings\u00a0of multiple lesions with complete ring enhancement and hypodensity in the arterial phase\u00a0fit best for \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic liver disease\u003C/strong\u003E.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydatid cysts\u003C/strong\u003E characteristically show daughter cysts within the main cyst.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple cysts \u003C/strong\u003Eare hypodense and would not show ring enhancement and have a barely visible wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemangiomas\u003C/strong\u003E are benign vascular lesions and are often an incidental finding. An haemangioma in the arterial phase would show irregular, nodular peripheral enhancement that may be discontinuous. In the case of a smaller lesion, it may also show uniform enhancement. This is not consistent with the ring enhancement seen in this image.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver abscess\u003C/strong\u003E may have ring\u00a0enhancement, but also may show pockets of air within the mass. The majority of patients with a liver abscess will have a fever and so this does not fit with the clinical picture.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A liver lesion that is hypodense on the arterial phase of a contrast-enhanced CT scan is very likely to malignant."],"references":["Mavilia M, Pakala T, Molina M, Wu G. Differentiating Cystic Liver Lesions: A Review of Imaging Modalities, Diagnosis and Management. J Clin Transl Hepatol. 2018; 6(2):208-216. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6018306/","Mortele K, Ros P. Cystic Focal Liver Lesions in the Adult: Differential CT and MR Imaging Features. RadioGraphics. 2001;21(4). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11452064/","Sica GT, Ji H, Ros PR. CT and MR imaging of hepatic metastases. AJR Am J Roentgenol. 2000;174(3):691-8. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10701611/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74897"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"229"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14565"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20681"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14565"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e46edddf-15d7-4380-a83c-701e0b3a7fec.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e46edddf-15d7-4380-a83c-701e0b3a7fec.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":438}},{"type":"media","id":"20681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20681"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/heDwaEvNSyeCHLBUXBHtfRxj7tTV4N.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/heDwaEvNSyeCHLBUXBHtfRxj7tTV4N.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":438}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74897"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T16:48:35+10:30","upda